1. Title

Image Denoising using Convolutional Autoencoder



2. Objective

The objective of this project is to develop a deep learning model that can remove noise from document images and improve their clarity. The model learns to transform noisy or blurred images into cleaner, more readable versions.



3. Dataset

The dataset consists of paired images:

Input (Noisy Images): Blurred or noisy document images
Output (Clean Images): Corresponding clean versions of the same documents

The dataset was preprocessed by:

Converting images to grayscale
Resizing images to 256×256
Normalizing pixel values between 0 and 1



4. Methodology

This project uses a Convolutional Autoencoder, a type of neural network designed for image reconstruction tasks.

Steps followed:

Load noisy and clean image pairs
Preprocess images (resize, normalize)

Train the model to learn mapping:

Noisy Image → Clean Image
Evaluate model on unseen images
Apply post-processing (sharpening) to improve output quality



5. Model Architecture

The model is based on a CNN Autoencoder with two main parts:

Encoder:
Extracts important features from the noisy image
Uses convolution and pooling layers
Decoder:
Reconstructs the clean image from encoded features
Uses upsampling and convolution layers

Key components:

Conv2D layers
MaxPooling layers
UpSampling layers
Activation: ReLU and Sigmoid

Loss Function: Mean Absolute Error (MAE)

Optimizer: Adam



6. Results

The model successfully reduces noise from document images and improves readability.

Observations:

Noisy images become clearer after processing
Text becomes more readable
Slight blurring remains due to reconstruction limitations

The model performs well on images similar to the training dataset.



7. Applications

This model can be used in:

Document Enhancement: Improving scanned or blurred documents
CCTV / Surveillance: Enhancing low-quality footage
Image Restoration: Cleaning old or degraded images
Mobile Photography: Improving low-light images



8. Conclusion

The project demonstrates that convolutional autoencoders can effectively reduce noise in document images. The model improves image clarity and readability, although some smoothing effects remain.

The performance depends on the similarity between training and testing data. Future improvements can include advanced models like U-Net or GANs for better sharpness.
